      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Vacuum leaks can indeed cause a lean condition. To find them, start by visually inspecting all vacuum lines and the intake manifold for cracks, holes, or loose connections. You can also perform a smoke test by introducing smoke into the vacuum system and watching for leaks where it escapes. Another method is to use a handheld vacuum gauge to check for a drop in vacuum pressure when the engine is running. If you find a leak, repair it by replacing the damaged hose or sealing the manifold with appropriate sealant. Remember, a tiny hole can sometimes be the culprit, so keep an eye out for the smallest of imperfections.",
